<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,536]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,463,151,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">General morphology.</emphasis>
Encrusting sponge measuring 
<quantity box="[852,900,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" unit="cm" value="1.0">1cm</quantity>
in diameter. Megascleres exclusively stout strongyles straight to slightly curved (
<number box="[583,684,188,213]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" value="232.5" valueMax="264.0" valueMin="201.0">201–264</number>
/ 
<number box="[694,764,188,213]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" value="19.5" valueMax="24.0" valueMin="15.0">15–24</number>
µm), smooth, rarely slender oxeas (
<figureCitation box="[1165,1235,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1976,1998]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1140,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,1140,1955]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Uruguaya corallioides: (a) megasclere strongyle; (b) megasclere oxea; (c) gemmuloscleres; (d) detail of gemmuloscleres surface. Scale bars: a, b, c— 50 µm, d— 5 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242088/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">
Fig. 
<number box="[1219,1235,188,213]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
a,b). Microscleres absent. Gemmuloscleres are granulated strongyles (
<number box="[761,835,223,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" value="70.5" valueMax="96.0" valueMin="45.0">45–96</number>
/ 
<number box="[844,913,223,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" value="13.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="12.0">12–15</number>
µm), short, stout (
<figureCitation box="[1131,1206,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1976,1998]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1140,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,1140,1955]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Uruguaya corallioides: (a) megasclere strongyle; (b) megasclere oxea; (c) gemmuloscleres; (d) detail of gemmuloscleres surface. Scale bars: a, b, c— 50 µm, d— 5 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242088/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">
Fig. 
<number box="[1190,1206,223,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
c,d). Gemmules are hemispherical, around 
<number box="[407,450,260,284]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" value="470.0">470</number>
µm in diameter, and gemmuloscleres are embedded tangentially.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
