<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="225" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,536]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,404,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[326,439,405,428]" class="Demospongiae" family="Potamolepidae" genus="Uruguaya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[326,439,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">Uruguaya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a monotypic genus with a restricted geographic range in the Neotropical Region. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,409,439,464]" class="Demospongiae" family="Potamolepidae" genus="Uruguaya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="corallioides">
<emphasis box="[151,409,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">Uruguaya corallioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a wide distribution in South 
<collectingCountry box="[806,906,439,464]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">America</collectingCountry>
. Furthermore, 
<collectingCountry box="[1078,1146,439,464]" name="Brazil" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">Brazil</collectingCountry>
has the most number of records for this species, mainly in north and south regions. Prior to the present study, however, it was unknown from northeast region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
